> Thanks for taking the time to report this.
> Can you please attach an example that shows the issue or missing feature?  (Must be openly licensed, completely self-contained so can directly run what you provide. Ideally use test_regress format, see https://veripool.org/guide/latest/contributing.html?highlight=test_regress#reporting-bugs)
> What output from that test indicates it is wrong, and what is the correct or expected output?  (Or, please make test self-checking if possible.)

I admit this testcase is a little bit far fetched (it also triggered discussion in yosys where it also triggered a disputed "bug" https://github.com/YosysHQ/yosys/issues/5487) 

```sv
module minimal (
    input logic clk,
    input logic [3:0] in_bus,
    output logic [3:0] out_bus
);
    logic [3:0] bus_reg;

    task automatic toggle(inout logic [3:0] bus);
        bus = ~bus;
    endtask

    always_ff @(posedge clk) begin
        bus_reg <= in_bus;
        toggle(bus_reg);
        out_bus <= bus_reg;
    end
endmodule
```

And the testbench

```sv
module top;
    logic [3:0] in_bus;
    logic [3:0] out_bus;
    logic clk;

    minimal dut (
        .in_bus(in_bus),
        .out_bus(out_bus),
        .clk(clk)
    );


    initial begin
        string line;
        int fd;
        int status;

        // Initialize hardcoded input values
        in_bus = 'h7;
        clk = 'h0;

        // Toggle clocks for several cycles with timeout protection
        // Set simulation timeout to prevent infinite loops
        fork
            begin
                #780;
                $display("ERROR: Simulation timeout after 780 time units");
                $finish;
            end
            begin
                repeat (50) begin
                    clk = 0;
                    #5;
                    clk = 1;
                    #5;
                end
            end
        join_any
        disable fork; // Kill timeout process

        #10; // Increased delay for settling

        $display("out_bus = %b (hex: %h)", out_bus, out_bus);
        assert(out_bus == 4'h8) else $error("Mismatch: expected out_bus = %h, got %h", 4'h8, out_bus);

        $finish;
    end
endmodule
```

This is what I make out of it :

According to IEEE 1800-2023 Section 4.9.7:
> "Subroutine argument passing is by value, and it copies in on invocation and copies out on return. The copy-out-on-the-return function behaves in the same manner as does any blocking assignment."

So from what I understand here we have:

- Active region: `always_ff` executes
  - `bus_reg <= in_bus;` -> schedules NBA for `bus_reg = in_bus` in NBA region
  - `toggle(bus_reg);` -> Executes immediately:
    - Copy-in: reads current `bus_reg` value
    - Modifies: `bus = ~bus`
    - Copy-out: writes back to `bus_reg` (blocking assignment in Active region)
  - `out_bus <= bus_reg;` -> schedules NBA for `out_bus = (modified bus_reg)` in NBA region
- NBA region
  - `bus_reg` gets the value from `in_bus` (overwriting the task modification)
  - `out_bus` gets the inverted original `bus_reg` value
`bus_reg <= in_bus` is in the NBA region

So we are expecting 1000 as output if 0111 is the input.

Verilator sends back 1111. I do not know if this is just an overcomplicated example for a smaller problem caused by "mixing" `<=` with `=`.

> What 'verilator' command line do we use to run your example?

```sh
verilator --binary --exe --build -Mdir obj_dir -sv --timing testbench.sv -I minimal.sv && ./obj_dir/Vtestbench
```

What 'verilator --version' are you using?  Did you try it with the git master version?  Did you try it with other simulators?

Upstream git verilator `Verilator 5.043 devel rev v5.042-59-gf32095dd1`

> What OS and distribution are you using?

linux arch

> May we assist you in trying to fix this in Verilator yourself?

I know for sure that this is far too complicated for me (if this is a bug and if this is what I think it is).

> (Please avoid attaching screenshots that show text - you can convert images to text using e.g. https://ocr.space)

Sorry if this is a duplicate of something else, sorry for the probably over complicated example. 

Thanks for maintaining verilator !

